arles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rendell|first=Matt|title=Blazing Saddles: The Cruel and Unusual History of the Tour de France|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=yWiCPwAACAAJ|date=2008|publisher=Quercus Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-84724-382-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Roche|first1=Stephen|last2=Cossins|first2=Peter|author-link=Stephen Roche|title=Born to Ride|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=HSeAMgEACAAJ|date=2012|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-22-409191-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Ryan|first1=Barry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LFc0DwAAQBAJ|title=The Ascent: Sean Kelly, Stephen Roche and the Rise of Irish Cycling's Golden Generation|date=2018|publisher=[[Gill (publisher)|Gill Books]]|location=Dublin|isbn=978-07171-8153-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Smith|editor-first=Martin|title=The Telegraph Book of the Tour de France|url=|year=2009|publisher=Aurum Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-84513-545-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Tour de France Rules and Statistics: 1903\u20132018|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=09sxwQEACAAJ|year=2018|publisher=Self-published|isbn=978-1-79398-080-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Van Gucht |first=Ruben |title=Hinault |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TicDBQAAQBAJ |year=2015 |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London |isbn=978-1-47-291296-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wheatcroft|first=Geoffrey|authorlink=Geoffrey Wheatcroft|title=Le Tour: A History of the Tour de France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CjAub7mpChgC|year=2013|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-4711-2894-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Woodland|editor-first=Les|title=The Yellow Jersey Companion to the Tour de France|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=QdMSjfvjDhUC|year=2007|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-22-408016-3|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Andrews|first=Guy|title=Greg Lemond: Yellow Jersey Racer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cGQXDQAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-4355-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Martin|first=Pierre|title=Tour 85: The Stories of the 1985 Tour of Italy and Tour de France|year=1985|publisher=Kennedy Brothers Publishing|location=Keighley, UK|asin=B010TGEBPY}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1985|1985 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1985 Tour de France|P|11|12|22}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1985 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1985 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1985 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:1985 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:June 1985 sports events in Europe|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1985 sports events in Europe|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "Zwerg Nase", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinal stages:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1985_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "Gillian R. Knapp", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Gillian R. Knapp\n| birth_place       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| fields            = [[Astronomy]]\n| workplaces        = {{Unbulleted list |[[Princeton University]] | [[California Institute of Technology]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{Unbulleted list |[[University of Maryland]] |[[University of Edinburgh]]}}\n| known_for         =  \n| awards            = \n}}\n'''Gillian Knapp''' is a professor of [[Astronomy and Astrophysics|astronomical sciences]] at [[Princeton University]]. She is a faculty fellow at [[Whitman College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/astro/people/faculty/gk/|title=Princeton|website=www.princeton.edu|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref> She has been involved in the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]]<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Icarus|volume=218|issue=1|title=Ensemble properties of comets in the Sloan Digital Sky Survey|doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2011.10.008|url=http://65.54.113.26/Publication/60708253/ensemble-properties-of-comets-in-the-sloan-digital-sky-survey|bibcode=2012Icar..218..571S|pages=571\u2013584|arxiv=1202.3999|access-date=2014-10-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028200951/http://65.54.113.26/Publication/60708253/ensemble-properties-of-comets-in-the-sloan-digital-sky-survey|archive-date=2014-10-28|url-status=dead|year=2012|last1=Solontoi|first1=Michael|last2=Ivezi\u0107|first2=\u017deljko|last3=Juri\u0107|first3=Mario|last4=Becker|first4=Andrew C.|last5=Jones|first5=Lynne|last6=West|first6=Andrew A.|last7=Kent|first7=Steve|last8=Lupton|first8=Robert H.|last9=Claire|first9=Mark|last10=Knapp|first10=Gillian R.|last11=Quinn|first11=Tom|last12=Gunn|first12=James E.|last13=Schneider|first13=Donald P.}}</ref> and she is an active member of the [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/3278/|title=International Astronomical Union|website=www.iau.org|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nGillian Knapp attended the [[University of Edinburgh]] and received her [[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc.]] in physics in 1966.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://resolver.caltech.edu/CaltechES:42.2.0|title=Engineering and Science, Volume 42:2, November-December 1978|last=Hutchings|first=Jr|date=1978|website=Engineering and Science|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Following her interest in astronomy, she moved to the US to continue her study in the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] where she got [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]]. in astronomy in 1971.<ref name=\":0\" /> After a short period of teaching in Maryland, Knapp moved to the [[West Coast of the United States|West coast]] in 1974 and continued her scientific career as a research fellow in the [[California Institute of Technology|California Institute of technology]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Scientific career ==\nIn the [[California Institute of Technology|California Institute of technology]], Gillian Knapp was promoted to a senior research fellow in 1976 and became a staff member of the [[Owens Valley Radio Observatory]] the same year.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1980 Knapp moved to Princeton to work as a researcher in the Department of Astrophysical Sciences of [[Princeton University]] and became an Associate Professor in 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nassauweekly.com/through-the-glass-ceiling-seeing-stars/|title=Through the Glass Ceiling, Seeing Stars|last=Eckstein|first=Nathan|date=2013-11-21|website=Nassau Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Starting 1990, she worked on the construction of the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]], and her contribution included the discovery and characterization of [[brown dwarf]]s, [[White dwarf|white dwarf stars]] and high-velocity stars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dof.princeton.edu/about/clerk-faculty/emeritus/gillian-r-knapp|title=Gillian R. Knapp {{!}} Dean of the Faculty|website=dof.princeton.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Her scientific career was successfully developed over the years in [[Princeton University]], where she received an [[Emeritus|Emerita]] Professor status in 2014.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2014/06/13/eight-faculty-members-transfer-emeritus-status|title=Eight faculty members transfer to emeritus status|website=Princeton University|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nGillian Knapp is a highly cited astronomer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=ZyH3HIAAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Gillian Knapp - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and a member of [[American Astronomical Society]], [[Royal Astronomical Society]], International Union of Radio Science, [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nIn 1983 the [[University of Texas at Austin]] established the [[Beatrice Tinsley]] Centennial Visiting Professorship in Astronomy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aauw.org/2014/07/16/beatrice-tinsley/|title=This Astronomer Had to Make the Hardest Career Choice|last=says|first=Online Articles That May Be of Interest to WIAReport Readers : Women In Academia Report|website=AAUW: Empowering Women Since 1881|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Gillian Knapp was the first recipient of the professorship (Fall 1985).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dCelxCnNfBoC&pg=PP240&lpg=PP240&dq=Beatrice+M.+Tinsley+Centennial+Visiting+Professorship+knapp#v=onepage|title=New Zealand Update|date=1980|publisher=New Zealand Embassy.|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKnapp was honored with the Distinguished Alumnus Award of the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.astro.umd.edu/resources/internal/awards/dept/alumnus.html|title=UMD Astronomy: Alumnus of the Year Award|website=www.astro.umd.edu|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nKnapp received the [https://web.astro.princeton.edu/news/presidential-award-stem-mentorship-awarded-gillian-knapp-professor-emerita-astrophysical Presidential Award for Excellence in Science, Mathematics and Engineering Mentoring] in 2018, for her work bringing college level course material to prison inmates as part of the [https://www.prisonteaching.org/ Prison Teaching Initiative], which she co-founded in 2005 along with other Princeton astrophysicists Mark Krumholz and [[Jenny Greene]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paesmem.net/paesmemRecognition/awardeeProfile/859?filterUpdate=true&awardeeName=knapp&state=&year=&category=&go=Find&max=10&offset=0&referer=AWARDEE_SEARCH|title=PAESMEM \u00bb Awardee Profile|website=paesmem.net|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is married to astronomer [[James E. Gunn (astronomer)|James Gunn]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knapp, Gillian R.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women astronomers]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:American Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:Royal Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:Women astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Women scientists]]\n[[Category:Astrophysicists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Gillian R. Knapp\n| birth_place       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| fields            = [[Astronomy]]\n| workplaces        = {{Unbulleted list |[[Princeton University]] | [[California Institute of Technology]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{Unbulleted list |[[University of Maryland]] |[[University of Edinburgh]]}}\n| known_for         =  \n| awards            = \n}}\n'''Gillian Knapp''' is a professor of [[Astronomy and Astrophysics|astronomical sciences]] at [[Princeton University]]. She is a faculty fellow at [[Whitman College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/astro/people/faculty/gk/|title=Princeton|website=www.princeton.edu|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref> She has been involved in the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]]<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Icarus|volume=218|issue=1|title=Ensemble properties of comets in the Sloan Digital Sky Survey|doi=10.1016/j.icarus.2011.10.008|url=http://65.54.113.26/Publication/60708253/ensemble-properties-of-comets-in-the-sloan-digital-sky-survey|bibcode=2012Icar..218..571S|pages=571\u2013584|arxiv=1202.3999|access-date=2014-10-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028200951/http://65.54.113.26/Publication/60708253/ensemble-properties-of-comets-in-the-sloan-digital-sky-survey|archive-date=2014-10-28|url-status=dead|year=2012|last1=Solontoi|first1=Michael|last2=Ivezi\u0107|first2=\u017deljko|last3=Juri\u0107|first3=Mario|last4=Becker|first4=Andrew C.|last5=Jones|first5=Lynne|last6=West|first6=Andrew A.|last7=Kent|first7=Steve|last8=Lupton|first8=Robert H.|last9=Claire|first9=Mark|last10=Knapp|first10=Gillian R.|last11=Quinn|first11=Tom|last12=Gunn|first12=James E.|last13=Schneider|first13=Donald P.}}</ref> and she is an active member of the [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/3278/|title=International Astronomical Union|website=www.iau.org|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nGillian Knapp attended the [[University of Edinburgh]] and received her [[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc.]] in physics in 1966.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://resolver.caltech.edu/CaltechES:42.2.0|title=Engineering and Science, Volume 42:2, November-December 1978|last=Hutchings|first=Jr|date=1978|website=Engineering and Science|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Following her interest in astronomy, she moved to the US to continue her study in the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] where she got [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]]. in astronomy in 1971.<ref name=\":0\" /> After a short period of teaching in Maryland, Knapp moved to the [[West Coast of the United States|West coast]] in 1974 and continued her scientific career as a research fellow in the [[California Institute of Technology|California Institute of technology]].<ref name=\":0\" /><br />\n\n== Scientific career ==\nIn the [[California Institute of Technology|California Institute of technology]], Gillian Knapp was promoted to a senior research fellow in 1976 and became a staff member of the [[Owens Valley Radio Observatory]] the same year.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1980 Knapp moved to Princeton to work as a researcher in the Department of Astrophysical Sciences of [[Princeton University]] and became an Associate Professor in 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nassauweekly.com/through-the-glass-ceiling-seeing-stars/|title=Through the Glass Ceiling, Seeing Stars|last=Eckstein|first=Nathan|date=2013-11-21|website=Nassau Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Starting 1990, she worked on the construction of the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]], and her contribution included the discovery and characterization of [[Brown dwarf|brown dwarfs]], [[White dwarf|white dwarf stars]] and high-velocity stars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dof.princeton.edu/about/clerk-faculty/emeritus/gillian-r-knapp|title=Gillian R. Knapp {{!}} Dean of the Faculty|website=dof.princeton.edu|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Her scientific career was successfully developed over the years in [[Princeton University]], where she received an [[Emeritus|Emerita]] Professor status in 2014.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2014/06/13/eight-faculty-members-transfer-emeritus-status|title=Eight faculty members transfer to emeritus status|website=Princeton University|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nGillian Knapp is a highly cited astronomer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=ZyH3HIAAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Gillian Knapp - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and a member of [[American Astronomical Society]], [[Royal Astronomical Society]], International Union of Radio Science, [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nIn 1983 the [[University of Texas at Austin]] established the [[Beatrice Tinsley]] Centennial Visiting Professorship in Astronomy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aauw.org/2014/07/16/beatrice-tinsley/|title=This Astronomer Had to Make the Hardest Career Choice|last=says|first=Online Articles That May Be of Interest to WIAReport Readers : Women In Academia Report|website=AAUW: Empowering Women Since 1881|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Gillian Knapp was the first recipient of the professorship (Fall 1985).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dCelxCnNfBoC&pg=PP240&lpg=PP240&dq=Beatrice+M.+Tinsley+Centennial+Visiting+Professorship+knapp#v=onepage|title=New Zealand Update|date=1980|publisher=New Zealand Embassy.|language=en}}</ref> \n\nKnapp was honored with the Distinguished Alumnus Award of the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.astro.umd.edu/resources/internal/awards/dept/alumnus.html|title=UMD Astronomy: Alumnus of the Year Award|website=www.astro.umd.edu|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> \n\nKnapp received the [https://web.astro.princeton.edu/news/presidential-award-stem-mentorship-awarded-gillian-knapp-professor-emerita-astrophysical Presidential Award for Excellence in Science, Mathematics and Engineering Mentoring] in 2018, for her work bringing college level course material to prison inmates as part of the [https://www.prisonteaching.org/ Prison Teaching Initiative], which she co-founded in 2005 along with other Princeton astrophysicists Mark Krumholz and [[Jenny Greene]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paesmem.net/paesmemRecognition/awardeeProfile/859?filterUpdate=true&awardeeName=knapp&state=&year=&category=&go=Find&max=10&offset=0&referer=AWARDEE_SEARCH|title=PAESMEM \u00bb Awardee Profile|website=paesmem.net|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is married to astronomer [[James E. Gunn (astronomer)|James Gunn]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knapp, Gillian R.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women astronomers]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:American Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:Royal Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:Women astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Women scientists]]\n[[Category:Astrophysicists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gillian_R._Knapp"}
{"title_page": "Geraldine Thomas", "text_new": "[[File:Geraldine Thomas lecturing in Adelaide, South Australia.jpg|alt=Geraldine Thomas lecturing in Adelaide, South Australia|thumb|Geraldine Thomas lecturing in Adelaide, South Australia]]\n'''Geraldine Anne Thomas''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} is a senior academic and Chair in Molecular Pathology at the Faculty of Medicine, Department of Surgery & Cancer, [[Imperial College London]]. She is an active researcher in fields of tissue banking and [[molecular pathology]] of [[Thyroid cancer|thyroid]] and [[breast cancer]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Home - Professor Geraldine Thomas|url = http://www.imperial.ac.uk/people/geraldine.thomas|website = www.imperial.ac.uk|accessdate = 2015-10-22}}</ref> Thomas is also a science communicator and has written opinion editorial pieces and provided comment to the media following the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Look at the science \u2013 smoking and obesity are more harmful than radiation {{!}} Geraldine Thomas|url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/apr/26/obesity-smoking-more-dangerous-radiation|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-10-22|first = Geraldine|last = Thomas}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Japan - The Next Wave - Foreign Correspondent - ABC|url = http://www.abc.net.au/foreign/content/2013/s3884420.htm|website = www.abc.net.au|accessdate = 2015-10-22}}</ref> In 2015 Thomas appeared in the TV documentary series ''[[Uranium \u2013 Twisting the Dragon\u2019s Tail|Uranium - Twisting the Dragon's Tail]]''  and was called to appear before the [[Nuclear Fuel Cycle Royal Commission]] in South Australia in October to answer the Commission's questions regarding the effects and threats of [[Ionizing radiation|radiation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nuclearrc.sa.gov.au/app/uploads/2015/10/151027-Topic-11-Day-1-v2.pdf |title=PUBLIC SESSION AGENDA: TOPIC 11 \u2013 EFFECTS AND THREATS OF RADIATION |date= |accessdate=2015-10-22 |website= |publisher=Nuclear Fuel Cycle Royal Commission |last= |first= }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As of 2016, Thomas is a member of [[UCL Australia|University College London Australia]]'s Nuclear Working Group.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.engineering.ucl.ac.uk/australia/nuclear-working-group/ |title=Nuclear Working Group UCL Australia |newspaper=UCL Australia |access-date=2016-11-02}}</ref>\n\nThomas made several predictions regarding cancer incidence in Japan following the Fukushima disaster. She told the Australian [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] in 2013:\n\n{{quote|Following Fukushima I doubt that there\u2019ll be any rise in thyroid cancers in Japan and this is simply because the amount of [[Radio Iodine|radio-iodine]] that was released post-Fukushima was much, much less than released post-Chernobyl. Absolutely if you look for a problem, especially if you\u2019re using incredibly sensitive technique which is what the Japanese are actually doing, you will find something. You will find part of that problem and you have to be careful you don\u2019t over interpret that and worry people unnecessarily.<ref name=\":0\" />}}\n\nThomas has stated that fear of the effects of radiation can be harmful,<ref>{{cite web |title=Bangkok Post article |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/640016/ |website=www.bangkokpost.com |accessdate=2015-10-22}}</ref> and has urged the media to report responsibly on the topic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GCTHsXGbpfs |title=Gerry Thomas Highlights Misconceptions over Health Impacts of Nuclear Accidents |date=2015-10-22 |accessdate= |website=Youtube.com |publisher=United Nations University}}</ref> Her position on nuclear hazards changed over time, and in 2015 she was quoted by the [[Minerals Council of Australia]] as having stated:\n{{quote|I can assure you that none of us are in the pay of the nuclear industry. I was [[Anti-nuclear movement|anti-nuclear]] until I worked on the after effects of the [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl accident]] \u2013 now I am very pro-nuclear as I realise that we have an unwarranted fear of radiation \u2013 probably due to all the rubbish about a [[nuclear winter]] we were fed during the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.minerals.org.au/file_upload/files/publications/Uranium_Natural_Energy_FINAL.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304022634/http://www.minerals.org.au/file_upload/files/publications/Uranium_Natural_Energy_FINAL.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-03-04 |title=URANIUM Natural Energy |publisher=Minerals Council of Australia |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-9925333-0-4 |pages=46}}</ref>}}\n\nThomas was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2019 Birthday Honours]] for services to science and public health.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62666|supp=y|page=B14|date=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Geraldine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:British women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women pathologists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Geraldine Thomas lecturing in Adelaide, South Australia.jpg|alt=Geraldine Thomas lecturing in Adelaide, South Australia|thumb|Geraldine Thomas lecturing in Adelaide, South Australia]]\n'''Geraldine Anne Thomas''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} is a senior academic and Chair in Molecular Pathology at the Faculty of Medicine, Department of Surgery & Cancer, [[Imperial College London]]. She is an active researcher in fields of tissue banking and [[molecular pathology]] of [[Thyroid cancer|thyroid]] and [[breast cancer]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Home - Professor Geraldine Thomas|url = http://www.imperial.ac.uk/people/geraldine.thomas|website = www.imperial.ac.uk|accessdate = 2015-10-22}}</ref> Thomas is also a science communicator and has written opinion editorial pieces and provided comment to the media following the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Look at the science \u2013 smoking and obesity are more harmful than radiation {{!}} Geraldine Thomas|url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/apr/26/obesity-smoking-more-dangerous-radiation|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-10-22|first = Geraldine|last = Thomas}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Japan - The Next Wave - Foreign Correspondent - ABC|url = http://www.abc.net.au/foreign/content/2013/s3884420.htm|website = www.abc.net.au|accessdate = 2015-10-22}}</ref> In 2015 Thomas appeared in the TV documentary series ''[[Uranium \u2013 Twisting the Dragon\u2019s Tail|Uranium - Twisting the Dragon's Tail]]''  and was called to appear before the [[Nuclear Fuel Cycle Royal Commission]] in South Australia in October to answer the Commission's questions regarding the effects and threats of [[Ionizing radiation|radiation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nuclearrc.sa.gov.au/app/uploads/2015/10/151027-Topic-11-Day-1-v2.pdf |title=PUBLIC SESSION AGENDA: TOPIC 11 \u2013 EFFECTS AND THREATS OF RADIATION |date= |accessdate=2015-10-22 |website= |publisher=Nuclear Fuel Cycle Royal Commission |last= |first= }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As of 2016, Thomas is a member of [[UCL Australia|University College London Australia]]'s Nuclear Working Group.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.engineering.ucl.ac.uk/australia/nuclear-working-group/ |title=Nuclear Working Group UCL Australia |newspaper=UCL Australia |access-date=2016-11-02}}</ref>\n\nThomas made several predictions regarding cancer incidence in Japan following the Fukushima disaster. She told the Australian [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] in 2013:\n\n{{quote|Following Fukushima I doubt that there\u2019ll be any rise in thyroid cancers in Japan and this is simply because the amount of [[Radio Iodine|radio-iodine]] that was released post-Fukushima was much, much less than released post-Chernobyl. Absolutely if you look for a problem, especially if you\u2019re using incredibly sensitive technique which is what the Japanese are actually doing, you will find something. You will find part of that problem and you have to be careful you don\u2019t over interpret that and worry people unnecessarily.<ref name=\":0\" />}}\n\nThomas has stated that fear of the effects of radiation can be harmful,<ref>{{cite web |title=Bangkok Post article |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/640016/ |website=www.bangkokpost.com |accessdate=2015-10-22}}</ref> and has urged the media to report responsibly on the topic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GCTHsXGbpfs |title=Gerry Thomas Highlights Misconceptions over Health Impacts of Nuclear Accidents |date=2015-10-22 |accessdate= |website=Youtube.com |publisher=United Nations University}}</ref> Her position on nuclear hazards changed over time, and in 2015 she was quoted by the [[Minerals Council of Australia]] as having stated:\n{{quote|I can assure you that none of us are in the pay of the nuclear industry. I was [[Anti-nuclear movement|anti-nuclear]] until I worked on the after effects of the [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl accident]] \u2013 now I am very pro-nuclear as I realise that we have an unwarranted fear of radiation \u2013 probably due to all the rubbish about a [[nuclear winter]] we were fed during the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.minerals.org.au/file_upload/files/publications/Uranium_Natural_Energy_FINAL.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304022634/http://www.minerals.org.au/file_upload/files/publications/Uranium_Natural_Energy_FINAL.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-03-04 |title=URANIUM Natural Energy |publisher=Minerals Council of Australia |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-9925333-0-4 |pages=46}}</ref>}}\n\nThomas was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2019 Birthday Honours]] for services to science and public health.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62666|supp=y|page=B14|date=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Geraldine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:British women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women pathologists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geraldine_Thomas"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Fauci", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Fauci|other people sharing this surname|Fauci (surname)}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American immunologist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Anthony Fauci\n|image = Anthony Fauci 2020.jpg\n|caption = Fauci in March 2020\n|office = Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]\n|term_start = November 2, 1984\n|term_end = \n|president = [[Ronald Reagan]]<br>[[George H.W. Bush]]<br>[[Bill Clinton]]<br>[[George W. Bush]]<br>[[Barack Obama]]<br>[[Donald Trump]]\n|predecessor = [[Richard M. Krause]]\n|successor = \n|birth_name = Anthony Stephen Fauci\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|12|24}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n|education = [[College of the Holy Cross]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Cornell University]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Christine Grady]]|1985}}\n|children = 3\n|awards = [[Maxwell Finland Award]] (1989)<br/>[[Ernst Jung Prize]] (1995)<br/>[[Lasker Award]] (2007)<br/>[[Presidential Medal of Freedom|Medal of Freedom]] (2008)<br/>[[Robert Koch Prize]] (Gold, 2013)\n|module = {{infobox scientist\n|embed = yes\n|fields = [[Immunology]]\n|workplaces = [[National Institutes of Health]], [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]}}\n}}\n'''Anthony Stephen Fauci''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|f|a\u028a|t\u0283|i|}}; born December 24, 1940) is an American physician and [[Immunology|immunologist]] who has served as the director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) since 1984. Since January 2020, he has been one of the lead members of the  [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump Administration's]] [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] addressing the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]]. Fauci is widely seen to be one of the most trusted medical figures in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/20/how-anthony-fauci-became-americas-doctor |title=How Anthony Fauci Became America\u2019s Doctor |last=Specter |first=Michael |website=The New Yorker |language=en|access-date=April 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413235133/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/20/how-anthony-fauci-became-americas-doctor|archive-date=April 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52027201 |title=The face of America's fight against Covid-19 |date=March 25, 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=April 13, 2020 |language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404215823/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52027201|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFauci is widely recognized as one of the world's leading experts on infectious diseases.<ref name=\"Alba_Frenkel\">{{cite web |last1=Alba |first1=Davey |last2=Frenkel |first2=Sheera |title=Medical Expert Who Corrects Trump Is Now a Target of the Far Right |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/technology/coronavirus-fauci-trump-conspiracy-target.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=March 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402135959/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/technology/coronavirus-fauci-trump-conspiracy-target.html |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Grady>Grady, Denise, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=1 \"Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327053240/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=1 |date=March 27, 2020 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 8, 11, 2020.</ref> As a physician with the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH), Fauci has served American public health in various capacities for over 50 years, and has been an advisor to every U.S. president since [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref name=\"Alba_Frenkel\" /> He has made contributions to [[HIV/AIDS research]] and other immunodeficiencies, both as a scientist and as the head of the NIAID at the NIH.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:VOA Interview Dr. Anthony S. Fauci.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man wearing a tie and a medium blue oxford button down shirt, seated in front of framed press clippings and awards, interviewed by medium-length blond-haired female interviewer about age 60, wearing a gray suit and yellow blouse| [[Greta Van Susteren]] interviewed Fauci in 2018 (38:18 minutes)]]\nFauci was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York City, to Stephen A. Fauci and Eugenia Abys Fauci, owners of a pharmacy. His father was a [[Columbia University]]-trained  [[pharmacist]], his mother and sister Denise worked the register, and Fauci delivered prescriptions. The pharmacy was located in the [[Dyker Heights]] section of Brooklyn, one neighborhood away from his family home in [[Bensonhurst]].<ref name=MedalBio/>\n\nFauci's paternal grandparents, Antonino Fauci and Calogera Guardino, were from [[Sciacca]], Italy. His maternal grandmother, Raffaella Trematerra, from [[Naples]], Italy, was a seamstress.  His maternal grandfather, Giovanni Abys, was born in Switzerland and was an artist, noted for landscape and portrait painting, magazine illustrations (Italy) as well graphic design for commercial labels, including olive oil cans. His grandparents emigrated from Italy to the United States in the late 19th century. Fauci grew up [[Catholic]].<ref name=MedalBio>{{cite journal |last1=Gallin |first1=John I. |title=Introduction of Anthony S. Fauci, MD |journal=Journal of Clinical Investigation |date=October 1, 2007 |volume=117 |issue=10 |pages=3131\u20133135 |pmid=17909634 |pmc=1994641 |doi=10.1172/jci33692}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fauci89: Transcription of oral history interview |url=http://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |publisher=NIH |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409183210/https://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |date=March 7, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/docs/fauci2_01.html |title=In Their Own Words |website=history.nih.gov|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325203026/https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/docs/fauci2_01.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFauci attended [[Regis High School (New York City)|Regis High School]] in Manhattan's [[Upper East Side]], where he [[captain (sports)|captained]] the school's basketball team and graduated in 1958.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunsinger Benbow |first=Dana |title=Donnie Walsh on losing basketball game to Dr. Anthony Fauci: 'How did that happen?' |date=April 2, 2020 |newspaper=The Indianapolis Star |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nba/pacers/2020/04/02/anthony-fauci-basketball-player-donnie-walsh-losing-fauci/5107766002/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403022035/https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nba/pacers/2020/04/02/anthony-fauci-basketball-player-donnie-walsh-losing-fauci/5107766002/|archive-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NIAID\"/> He then went to the [[College of the Holy Cross]], graduating in 1962 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[classics]]. Fauci then attended medical school at [[Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University|Cornell University Medical College]] where he graduated first in his class with a [[Doctor of Medicine]] in 1966.<ref name=MedalBio/> He then completed an internship and [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[internal medicine]] at the [[New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center]], now known as New York Presbyterian/Weill Cornell Medicine.<ref name=\"NIAID\">{{cite web |title=Biography Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. NIAID Director |url=http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/ |publisher=NIAID |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030171118/http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/ |archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{external media| float = right| width=230px| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?323680-1/qa-dr-anthony-fauci ''Q&A'' interview with Fauci on his life and career, January 18, 2015], [[C-SPAN]]}} \n[[File:Dr Anthony Fauci-America's Man on Infectious Diseases-VoA.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man in wearing a suit and seated on a chair in a lab, mixed with shots of female coworkers working with laboratory equipment|Fauci discusses his work in 2020 (4 minutes)]]\nIn 1968, Fauci joined the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH) as a clinical associate in the Laboratory of Clinical Investigation (LCI) at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.<ref name=\"pr1984\"/> In 1974, he became Head of the Clinical Physiology Section, LCI, and in 1980 was appointed Chief of the Laboratory of Immunoregulation. In 1984, he became director of NIAID, a position he still holds as of 2020.<ref name = Grady/> In that role he has the responsibility for an extensive research portfolio of basic and applied research on infectious and immune-mediated illnesses.<ref name=\"pr1984\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Anthony Fauci Named New NIAID Director |url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/assets/media/pdf/press/1984/PR_NIAID_1984_11_02.pdf |website=HHS News |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |format=Press release |date=November 2, 1984 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209135255/https://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/press/1984/PR_NIAID_1984_11_02.pdf |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> He has turned down several offers to lead his agency's parent, the NIH, and has been at the forefront of US efforts to contend with viral diseases like HIV, [[SARS]], the [[2009 swine flu pandemic]], [[MERS]], [[Ebola]] and [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grady |first1=Denise |title=Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html |work=The New York Times |publisher=New York Times Company |date=March 8, 2020 |location=New York |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315113453/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe played a significant role in the early 2000s in creating the [[President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Varmus |first=Harold |title=Making PEPFAR |journal=Science & Diplomacy |date=December 1, 2013 |volume=2 |issue=4 |url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2013/making-pepfar|access-date=December 2, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203002438/http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2013/making-pepfar|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and in driving development of [[biodefense]] drugs and vaccines following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 terrorist attacks]].<ref>Bernard Wysocki Jr for The Wall Street Journal. December 6, 2005 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113383825463714813 Agency Chief Spurs Bioterror Research \u2013 And Controversy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229204855/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113383825463714813 |date=February 29, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a visiting professor at many medical centers, and has received 30 honorary doctorates from universities in the US and abroad.<ref name=\"Cited\"/>\n\n===Medical achievements===\n[[File:President Clinton meets with Dr. Anthony Fauci (14358494424).jpg|thumb|left|President [[Bill Clinton]] visits the NIH in 1995 and hears about the latest advances in HIV/AIDS research from Fauci]]\n[[File:President George W. Bush and Dr. Anthony S. Fauci.jpg|thumb|right|Fauci poses for a photo with [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] in 2007]]\nFauci has made important scientific observations that contributed to the understanding of regulation of the human immune response, and is recognized for delineating the mechanisms whereby [[Immunosuppression|immunosuppressive]] agents adapt to that response. He developed therapies for formerly fatal diseases such as [[polyarteritis nodosa]], [[granulomatosis with polyangiitis]], and [[lymphomatoid granulomatosis]]. In a 1985 [[Stanford University]] Arthritis Center Survey of the American Rheumatism Association, membership ranked Fauci's work on the treatment of polyarteritis nodosa and granulomatosis with polyangiitis as one of the most important advances in patient management in [[rheumatology]] over the previous 20 years.<ref name=\"Holy Cross\">Holy Cross Magazine [http://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/summer02/features/fauci_sidebar.html Anthony S. Fauci, M.D., \u201962] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823163730/http://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/summer02/features/fauci_sidebar.html |date=August 23, 2016 }} Retrieved on May 30, 2007</ref><ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\">{{cite web |title=1998 AACC Lectureship Award |url=https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx |publisher=American Association for Clinical Chemistry |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102191524/https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx |archivedate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:President Obama greets Dr Anthony Fauci 9203044910 l (14352845344).jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] greets Fauci in June 2014]]\nFauci has contributed to the understanding of how [[HIV]] destroys the body's defenses leading to the progression to [[AIDS]]. He has outlined the mechanisms of induction of HIV expression by endogenous [[cytokine]]s.<ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\" /> Fauci has worked to develop strategies for the therapy and immune reconstitution of patients with the disease, as well as for a [[vaccine]] to prevent HIV infection. His current research is concentrated on identifying the nature of the immunopathogenic mechanisms of HIV infection and the scope of the body's immune responses to HIV.\n\nIn 2003, the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] stated that from 1983 to 2002, \"Fauci was the 13th most-cited scientist among the 2.5 to 3 million authors in all disciplines throughout the world who published articles in scientific journals\".<ref name=\"NIAID\"/>\n\n=== Ebola Congressional hearing ===\n{{See also|Ebola virus cases in the United States}}\nOn October 16, 2014, in a United States Congressional hearing regarding the [[Ebola virus]] crisis, Fauci, who, as the director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) had been discussing the importance of screening for weeks,<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2014/10/06/more-ebola-screening-possible-for-united-states Officials eyeing additional screening for Ebola in US, vow to protect citizens from disease] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305023606/http://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2014/10/06/more-ebola-screening-possible-for-united-states |date=March 5, 2016 }}. Associated Press. October 6, 2014.  Retrieved October 16, 2014.</ref> testified that NIAID was still some distance away from producing sufficient quantities of cures or vaccines for widespread trials.<ref name=2014-Guardian-EbolaHearing>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Dan |title=CDC director warns Ebola like 'forest fire' as Congress readies for hearing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/ebola-congress-hearing-cdc-director |work=The Guardian |date=October 16, 2014|access-date=December 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503184455/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/ebola-congress-hearing-cdc-director|archive-date=May 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Specifically, Fauci said, \"While NIAID is an active participant in the global effort to address the public health emergency occurring in west Africa, it is important to recognize that we are still in the early stages of understanding how infection with the Ebola virus can be treated and prevented.\" <ref name=2014-Guardian-EbolaHearing />\n\nFauci also remarked in the hearing: \"As we continue to expedite research while enforcing high safety and efficacy standards, the implementation of the public health measures already known to contain prior Ebola virus outbreaks and the implementation of treatment strategies such as fluid and electrolyte replacement are essential to preventing additional infections, treating those already infected, protecting healthcare providers, and ultimately bringing this epidemic to an end.\"<ref name=2014-Guardian-EbolaHearing />\n\n===COVID-19 task force===\n[[File:White House Coronavirus Update Briefing (49723232743).jpg|thumb|Fauci speaks to the [[White House]] press corps on [[COVID-19]] in March 2020]]\nFauci is a member of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] established in late January 2020, under [[President Trump]], to deal with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=WhatWeKnow>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/27/coronavirus-what-we-know-mike-pence-and-task-force/4891905002/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |title=What we know about the White House coronavirus task force now that Mike Pence is in charge |author=Santucci, Jeanine |date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229101529/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/27/coronavirus-what-we-know-mike-pence-and-task-force/4891905002/ |archive-date= February 29, 2020 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"scimag-22mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title='I'm going to keep pushing.' Anthony Fauci tries to make the White House listen to facts of the pandemic |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/i-m-going-keep-pushing-anthony-fauci-tries-make-white-house-listen-facts-pandemic |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[Science Magazine]] |date=March 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323021843/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/i-m-going-keep-pushing-anthony-fauci-tries-make-white-house-listen-facts-pandemic |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> He said that the final [[case fatality rate]] of those who are infected will likely be closer to 1% than the 2% initially estimated by the [[World Health Organization]], which is ten times the 0.1% reported rate for seasonal flu.<ref>Higgins-Dunn, Noah; Lovelace, Berkely, Jr., [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/top-federal-health-official-says-coronavirus-outbreak-is-going-to-get-worse-in-the-us.html \"Top US health official says the coronavirus is 10 times 'more lethal' than the seasonal flu\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323055620/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/top-federal-health-official-says-coronavirus-outbreak-is-going-to-get-worse-in-the-us.html |date=March 23, 2020 }}, ''[[CNBC]]'', March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>McCormack, John, [https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-the-difference-between-a-1-and-0-1-fatality-rate-is-huge/ \"Coronavirus vs. the Flu: The Difference Between a 1% and 0.1% Fatality Rate Is Huge\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322140426/https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-the-difference-between-a-1-and-0-1-fatality-rate-is-huge/ |date=March 22, 2020 }}, ''[[National Review]]'', March 14, 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trump Has Given Unusual Leeway to Fauci, but Aides Say He's Losing His Patience |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-fauci.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200324&instance_id=17020&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=104839084&section=topNews&segment_id=22704&te=1&user_id=c001b63136aba3268ed514b0835032af |website=The New York Times |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326181422/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-fauci.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200324&instance_id=17020&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=104839084&section=topNews&segment_id=22704&te=1&user_id=c001b63136aba3268ed514b0835032af |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a \"de facto\" public health spokesperson for the office of the President during the pandemic<ref name=2020-Atlantic-Profile>{{cite news |last1=Nicholas |first1=Peter |title=Anthony Fauci\u2019s Plan to Stay Honest |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/anthony-fauci-covid-19-trump-and-staying-healthy/608554/ |work=The Atlantic |date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134643/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/anthony-fauci-covid-19-trump-and-staying-healthy/608554/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-reasons-gov-cuomo-and-dr-fauci-are-americas-de-facto-leaders-during-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2020-03-30 |title=5 reasons Gov. Cuomo and Dr. Fauci are America's de facto leaders during the coronavirus pandemic |last=Smith |first=Virginia K. |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201903/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-reasons-gov-cuomo-and-dr-fauci-are-americas-de-facto-leaders-during-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2020-03-30|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and strong advocate of ongoing social distancing efforts in the United States. On March 29 he argued for the extension of the initial 15-day self-isolation guidelines, issued by the executive office, to at least until the end of April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5812439/trump-coronavirus-measures-fauci/ |title=President Trump's Advisors 'Argued Strongly' Against Easing Coronavirus Measures Too Early, Anthony Fauci Says |website=Time |language=en|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150259/https://time.com/5812439/trump-coronavirus-measures-fauci/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to his disagreements with Trump, Fauci has been criticised by right-wing pundits and received death threats that resulted in the need for a security detail.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/490763-fauci-dismisses-death-threats-its-my-job |title=Fauci dismisses death threats: 'It's my job' |last=Budryk |first=Zack |date=April 2, 2020 |website=TheHill |language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404061334/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/490763-fauci-dismisses-death-threats-its-my-job|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/politics/anthony-fauci-security-detail/index.html |title=Nation's top coronavirus expert Dr. Anthony Fauci forced to beef up security as death threats increase |author1=Kate Bennett |author2=Evan Perez |website=CNN|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402041259/https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/politics/anthony-fauci-security-detail/index.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/01/dr-fauci-security-reportedly-expanded-as-infectious-disease-expert-faces-threats |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403172130/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/01/dr-fauci-security-reportedly-expanded-as-infectious-disease-expert-faces-threats |archive-date=April 3, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> While there have been disagreements, Trump has also praised Fauci.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump offers praise for absent Fauci: 'He's a good man' |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/489145-trump-offers-praise-for-nihs-fauci-hes-a-good-man |work=The Hill |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406151121/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/489145-trump-offers-praise-for-nihs-fauci-hes-a-good-man |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who is Dr Anthony Fauci, the US's trusted voice on coronavirus? |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/dr-anthony-fauci-trusted-voice-coronavirus-200330124431910.html |work=Al Jazeera |date=March 30, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401052651/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/dr-anthony-fauci-trusted-voice-coronavirus-200330124431910.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=How Fauci Prods, Persuades Trump on Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-coronavirus-crisis-deepens-trump-and-fauci-form-complicated-bond-11585682074 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402013651/https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-coronavirus-crisis-deepens-trump-and-fauci-form-complicated-bond-11585682074 |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFauci married [[Christine Grady]], a nurse and [[bioethicist]] with the NIH, in 1985, after they met while treating a patient. Grady is chief of the Department of Bioethics at the [[National Institutes of Health Clinical Center]]. The couple has three adult daughters: Jennifer, Megan, and Alison.<ref name=\"Heavy31320\">{{cite news |last1=Laviola |first1=Erin |title=Christine Grady, Anthony Fauci's Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/christine-grady-anthony-fauci-wife/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Heavy.com |date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140746/https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/christine-grady-anthony-fauci-wife/ |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nFauci is a member of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[National Academy of Medicine]], the [[American Philosophical Society]], and the [[Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters]], as well as other numerous professional societies including the [[American Society for Clinical Investigation]], the [[Infectious Diseases Society of America]], and the [[American Association of Immunologists]]. He serves on the editorial boards of many scientific journals; as an editor of ''[[Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine]]''; and as author, coauthor, or editor of more than 1,000 scientific publications, including several textbooks.<ref name=\"Cited\">Highly Cited [http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 Biography] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120428/http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 |date=September 29, 2007 }} Retrieved May 30, 2007</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:Ben Carson and Anthony Fauci.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ben Carson]] and Anthony Fauci (right) being announced as recipients of the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] at the [[White House]] on June 19, 2008.]]\n* 1979: [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]]<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |title=Press Release Archive: Twelve Outstanding Public Servants Representing the Best and Brightest in Federal Government to be Honored at 53rd Annual Arthur S. Flemming Awards Presented by GW June 11 |url=https://www2.gwu.edu/~media/pressreleases/06-06-02-FlemmingAdvisory.htm |website=www2.gwu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902123738/http://www.gwu.edu/~media/pressreleases/06-06-02-FlemmingAdvisory.htm|archive-date=September 2, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1993: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Bates College]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bates.edu/president/list-of-honorary-degree-recipients/|title=List of Honorary Degree Recipients {{!}} Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, D.Sc. {{!}} Bates College|last=|first=|date=May 31, 1993|website=Bates College|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 10, 2020|quote=Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, D.Sc. (May 31, 1993)}}</ref>\n*1995: [[Ernst Jung Prize]] (shared with Samuel A. Wells, Jr.)<ref>{{cite web |title=All Laureates \u2013 English |url=http://www.jung-stiftung.de/en/die-jung-stiftung-1/ernst-jung-preis-fuer-medizin/alle-preistraeger |publisher=Jung Foundation for Science and Research |accessdate=November 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033100/http://www.jung-stiftung.de/en/die-jung-stiftung-1/ernst-jung-preis-fuer-medizin/alle-preistraeger|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*1995: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Duke University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goduke.com/news/2020/4/2/mens-basketball-dr-fauci-joined-coach-k-for-todays-basketball-beyond.aspx|title=SiriusXM's Basketball and Beyond with Coach K: Dr. Anthony Fauci|website=Duke University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n* 1996: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Colgate University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/july1996/honorary-degrees.html |title=Honoris causa |website=Colgate University | access-date=March 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825105159/http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/july1996/honorary-degrees.html | archive-date=August 25, 2007 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1999: Honorary Doctor of Public Service Degree, [[Shippensburg University of Pennsylvania]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Agencies|first=United States Congress House Committee on Appropriations Subcommittee on the Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Related|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4a7SoQfEz2QC&pg=PA954&lpg=PA954&dq=1999:+Honorary+Doctor+of+Public+Service+Degree,+Shippensburg+University+of+Pennsylvania+fauci&source=bl&ots=MhsDHP48RA&sig=ACfU3U1lsj-_9WWVxxx13X85g3a97pSklg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjquruVyPDoAhVEs54KHY1sDRkQ6AEwAHoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=1999:%20Honorary%20Doctor%20of%20Public%20Service%20Degree,%20Shippensburg%20University%20of%20Pennsylvania%20fauci&f=false|title=Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Related Agencies Appropriations for 2001: Hearings Before a Subcommittee of the Committee on Appropriations, House of Representatives, One Hundred Sixth Congress, Second Session|date=2000|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=978-0-16-060655-7|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2002: [[Albany Medical Center Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Lawrence K. Altman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/28/us/aids-researcher-fauci-wins-prize.html |title=AIDS Researcher Fauci Wins Prize |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 28, 2002 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527213848/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/28/us/aids-researcher-fauci-wins-prize.html |archive-date=May 27, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[American Academy of Achievement]]'s Golden Plate Award<ref name = AAA>{{cite web |title=Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. Biography and Interview |website=achievement.org |publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]] |url=https://www.achievement.org/achiever/anthony-s-fauci-m-d/#interview|access-date=April 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208114942/http://www.achievement.org/achiever/anthony-s-fauci-m-d/#interview|archive-date=February 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[National Medal of Science]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=5300000000430 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details |publisher=[[National Science Foundation]] |date=July 27, 2007 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401062952/https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=5300000000430 |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[American Association of Immunologists Lifetime Achievement Award]]<ref name=\"Winners\">{{cite web |title=Past Recipients |website=The American Association of Immunologists |url=https://www.aai.org/Awards/Career-Awards/AAI-Lifetime-Achievement-Award/Past-Recipients.aspx | access-date=September 19, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919212957/https://www.aai.org/Awards/Career-Awards/AAI-Lifetime-Achievement-Award/Past-Recipients.aspx | archive-date=September 19, 2018 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2007: [[Mary Woodard Lasker Public Service Award]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Altman |first1=Lawrence K. |title=4 Winners of Lasker Medical Prize |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/16/health/16lasker.html?ref=us |work=The New York Times |date=September 16, 2007|access-date=February 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033315/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/16/health/16lasker.html?ref=us|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2007: [[George M. Kober Medal]], [[Association of American Physicians]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gallin |first1=John I. |title=2007 Association of American Physicians George M. Kober Medal: Introduction of Anthony S. Fauci, MD |journal=The Journal of Clinical Investigation |volume=117:3131\u20133135 (2007) |doi=10.1172/JCI33692|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]<ref name = AAA/>\n* 2013: [[Robert Koch Gold Medal]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=81&clang=1 |title=Robert Koch Stiftung - Anthony S. Fauci |website=www.robert-koch-stiftung.de|access-date=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912231646/http://robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=81&clang=1|archive-date=September 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2013: [[Prince Mahidol Award]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.princemahidolaward.org/people/dr-anthony-fauci/ |title=Dr. Anthony Fauci |date=November 21, 2013 |website=Prince Mahidol Award Foundation}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[John Dirks Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]]<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)30050-2/abstract |title=NIAID director wins Canada Gairdner Global Health Award |first=Brian |last=Owens |date=March 26, 2016 |journal=The Lancet |volume=387 |issue=10025 |pages=1261 |via=www.thelancet.com |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)30050-2 |pmid=27017308|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n*2018: Honorary Doctor of Science, Commencement Speaker, [[American University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.american.edu/media/news/20180418-commencement-2018.cfm|title=AU Announces 2018 Commencement Speakers|last=Alex|first=Kelly|last2=April 18|first2=er {{!}}|website=American University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23|last3=2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works and publications==\n{{Scholia|author}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Dale|first2=David C.|last3=Balow|first3=James E.|title=Glucocorticosteroid Therapy: Mechanisms of Action and Clinical Considerations|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=March 1976|volume=84|issue=3|pages=304-15|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-84-3-304|pmid=769625|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/690158/glucocorticosteroid-therapy-mechanisms-action-clinical-considerations?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-84-3-304}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34058573|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Haynes|first2=Barton F.|last3=Katz|first3=Paul|title=The Spectrum of Vasculitis: Clinical, Pathologic, Immunologic, and Therapeutic Considerations|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=November 1, 1978|volume=89|issue=5_Part_1|pages=660|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-89-5-660|pmid=31121|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/692458/spectrum-vasculitis-clinical-pathologic-immunologic-therapeutic-considerations?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-89-5-660}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34049019|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Haynes|first2=Barton F.|last3=Katz|first3=Paul|last4=Wolff|first4=Sheldon M.|title=Wegener's Granulomatosis: Prospective Clinical and Therapeutic Experience With 85 Patients for 21 Years|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=January 1983|volume=98|issue=1|pages=76|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-98-1-76|pmid=6336643|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/696194/wegener-s-granulomatosis-prospective-clinical-therapeutic-experience-85-patients-21?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-98-1-76}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34055385|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Macher|first2=Abe M.|last3=Longo|first3=Dan L.|last4=Lane|first4=H. Clifford|last5=Rook|first5=Alain H.|last6=Masur|first6=Henry|last7=Gelmann|first7=Edward P.|title=Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome: Epidemiologic, Clinical, Immunologic, and Therapeutic Considerations|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=January 1984|volume=100|issue=1|pages=92|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-100-1-92|pmid=6318629|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/697649/acquired-immunodeficiency-syndrome-epidemiologic-clinical-immunologic-therapeutic-considerations?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-100-1-92}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34055324|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=AS|title=The human immunodeficiency virus: infectivity and mechanisms of pathogenesis|journal=Science|date=February 5, 1988|volume=239|issue=4840|pages=617\u2013622|doi=10.1126/science.3277274|pmid=3277274|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/239/4840/617}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34049376|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Pantaleo|first1=Giuseppe|last2=Graziosi|first2=Cecilia|last3=Fauci|first3=Anthony S.|title=The Immunopathogenesis of Human Immunodeficiency Virus Infection|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|date=February 4, 1993|volume=328|issue=5|pages=327\u2013335|doi=10.1056/NEJM199302043280508|pmid=8093551|url=https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199302043280508}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34060285|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|title=Host factors and the pathogenesis of HIV-induced disease|journal=Nature|date=December 1996|volume=384|issue=6609|pages=529\u2013534|doi=10.1038/384529A0|pmid=8955267|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/384529a0}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34063826|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Morens|first1=David M.|last2=Folkers|first2=Gregory K.|last3=Fauci|first3=Anthony S.|title=The challenge of emerging and re-emerging infectious diseases|journal=Nature|date=July 8, 2004|volume=430|issue=6996|pages=242\u2013249|doi=10.1038/nature02759|pmid=15241422|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature02759|doi-access=free}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q29617354|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Morens|first1=David M.|last2=Fauci|first2=Anthony S.|title=The 1918 Influenza Pandemic: Insights for the 21st Century|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=April 2007|volume=195|issue=7|pages=1018\u20131028|doi=10.1086/511989|doi-access=free|pmid=17330793|url=https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/195/7/1018/800918}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q30230070|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Johnston|first1=Margaret I.|last2=Fauci|first2=Anthony S.|title=An HIV Vaccine \u2014 Challenges and Prospects|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|date=August 28, 2008|volume=359|issue=9|pages=888\u2013890|doi=10.1056/NEJMp0806162|pmid=18753644|doi-access=free|url=https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMp0806162}}{{Wikidata+icon|Q34013570|y}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Fauci|editor1-first=Anthony S.|editor2-last=Harrison|editor2-first=Ross|title=Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine|publisher=McGraw-Hill Medical|isbn=978-0-07-159991-7|edition=17th|oclc=1109159992}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Lane|first2=H. Clifford|last3=Redfield|first3=Robert R.|author-link3=Robert R. Redfield|title=Covid-19 \u2014 Navigating the Uncharted|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|date=March 26, 2020|volume=382|issue=13|pages=1268\u20131269|doi=10.1056/NEJMe2002387|doi-access=free|pmid=32109011|url=https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMe2002387}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Unger, Donald N.S., [https://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/2002_03Summer.pdf \"I Saw People Who Were In Pain\"], ''Holy Cross Magazine'', College of the Holy Cross,  v.36, n.3, Summer 2002 issue. Front cover and pp.10-19.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anthony&nbsp;Fauci}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.niaid.nih.gov/about/director Anthony S. Fauci, M.D.] at [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID)\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=Anthony%20S%20Fauci Anthony S. Fauci] at [[PubMed]]\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm2118834|Anthony Fauci}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Biography}}\n\n{{Winners of the National Medal of Science|biological}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fauci, Anthony S.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American immunologists]]\n[[Category:American medical researchers]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:College of the Holy Cross alumni]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:National Institutes of Health people]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Science laureates]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Regis High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Weill Cornell Medical College alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Coronavirus Task Force]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-Italian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Fauci|other people sharing this surname|Fauci (surname)}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American immunologist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Anthony Fauci\n|image = Anthony Fauci 2020.jpg\n|caption = Fauci in March 2020\n|office = Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]\n|term_start = November 2, 1984\n|term_end = \n|president = [[Ronald Reagan]]<br>[[George H.W. Bush]]<br>[[Bill Clinton]]<br>[[George W. Bush]]<br>[[Barack Obama]]<br>[[Donald Trump]]\n|predecessor = [[Richard M. Krause]]\n|successor = \n|birth_name = Anthony Stephen Fauci\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|12|24}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n|education = [[College of the Holy Cross]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Cornell University]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Christine Grady]]|1985}}\n|children = 3\n|awards = [[Maxwell Finland Award]] (1989)<br/>[[Ernst Jung Prize]] (1995)<br/>[[Lasker Award]] (2007)<br/>[[Presidential Medal of Freedom|Medal of Freedom]] (2008)<br/>[[Robert Koch Prize]] (Gold, 2013)\n|module = {{infobox scientist\n|embed = yes\n|fields = [[Immunology]]\n|workplaces = [[National Institutes of Health]], [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]}}\n}}\n'''Anthony Stephen Fauci''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|f|a\u028a|t\u0283|i|}}; born December 24, 1940) is an American physician and [[Immunology|immunologist]] who has served as the director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) since 1984. Since January 2020, he has been one of the lead members of the  [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump Administration's]] [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] addressing the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]]. Fauci is widely seen to be one of the most trusted medical figures in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/20/how-anthony-fauci-became-americas-doctor |title=How Anthony Fauci Became America\u2019s Doctor |last=Specter |first=Michael |website=The New Yorker |language=en|access-date=April 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413235133/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/04/20/how-anthony-fauci-became-americas-doctor|archive-date=April 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52027201 |title=The face of America's fight against Covid-19 |date=March 25, 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=April 13, 2020 |language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404215823/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52027201|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFauci is widely recognized as one of the world's leading experts on infectious diseases.<ref name=\"Alba_Frenkel\">{{cite web |last1=Alba |first1=Davey |last2=Frenkel |first2=Sheera |title=Medical Expert Who Corrects Trump Is Now a Target of the Far Right |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/technology/coronavirus-fauci-trump-conspiracy-target.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=March 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402135959/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/technology/coronavirus-fauci-trump-conspiracy-target.html |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Grady>Grady, Denise, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=1 \"Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327053240/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=1 |date=March 27, 2020 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 8, 11, 2020.</ref> As a physician with the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH), Fauci has served American public health in various capacities for over 50 years, and has been an advisor to every U.S. president since [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref name=\"Alba_Frenkel\" /> He has made contributions to [[HIV/AIDS research]] and other immunodeficiencies, both as a scientist and as the head of the NIAID at the NIH.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:VOA Interview Dr. Anthony S. Fauci.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man wearing a tie and a medium blue oxford button down shirt, seated in front of framed press clippings and awards, interviewed by medium-length blond-haired female interviewer about age 60, wearing a gray suit and yellow blouse| [[Greta Van Susteren]] interviewed Fauci in 2018 (38:18 minutes)]]\nFauci was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York City, to Stephen A. Fauci and Eugenia Abys Fauci, owners of a pharmacy. His father was a [[Columbia University]]-trained  [[pharmacist]], his mother and sister Denise worked the register, and Fauci delivered prescriptions. The pharmacy was located in the [[Dyker Heights]] section of Brooklyn, one neighborhood away from his family home in [[Bensonhurst]].<ref name=MedalBio/>\n\nFauci's paternal grandparents, Antonino Fauci and Calogera Guardino, were from [[Sciacca]], Italy. His maternal grandmother, Raffaella Trematerra, from [[Naples]], Italy, was a seamstress.  His maternal grandfather, Giovanni Abys, was born in Switzerland and was an artist, noted for landscape and portrait painting, magazine illustrations (Italy) as well graphic design for commercial labels, including olive oil cans. His grandparents emigrated from Italy to the United States in the late 19th century. Fauci grew up [[Catholic]].<ref name=MedalBio>{{cite journal |last1=Gallin |first1=John I. |title=Introduction of Anthony S. Fauci, MD |journal=Journal of Clinical Investigation |date=October 1, 2007 |volume=117 |issue=10 |pages=3131\u20133135 |pmid=17909634 |pmc=1994641 |doi=10.1172/jci33692}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fauci89: Transcription of oral history interview |url=http://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |publisher=NIH |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409183210/https://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |date=March 7, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/docs/fauci2_01.html |title=In Their Own Words |website=history.nih.gov|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325203026/https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/docs/fauci2_01.html|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFauci attended [[Regis High School (New York City)|Regis High School]] in Manhattan's [[Upper East Side]], where he [[captain (sports)|captained]] the school's basketball team and graduated in 1958.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunsinger Benbow |first=Dana |title=Donnie Walsh on losing basketball game to Dr. Anthony Fauci: 'How did that happen?' |date=April 2, 2020 |newspaper=The Indianapolis Star |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nba/pacers/2020/04/02/anthony-fauci-basketball-player-donnie-walsh-losing-fauci/5107766002/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403022035/https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nba/pacers/2020/04/02/anthony-fauci-basketball-player-donnie-walsh-losing-fauci/5107766002/|archive-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NIAID\"/> He then went to the [[College of the Holy Cross]], graduating in 1962 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[classics]]. Fauci then attended medical school at [[Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University|Cornell University Medical College]] where he graduated first in his class with a [[Doctor of Medicine]] in 1966.<ref name=MedalBio/> He then completed an internship and [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[internal medicine] at the [[New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center]], now known as New York Presbyterian/Weill Cornell Medicine.<ref name=\"NIAID\">{{cite web |title=Biography Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. NIAID Director |url=http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/ |publisher=NIAID |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030171118/http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/ |archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{external media| float = right| width=230px| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?323680-1/qa-dr-anthony-fauci ''Q&A'' interview with Fauci on his life and career, January 18, 2015], [[C-SPAN]]}} \n[[File:Dr Anthony Fauci-America's Man on Infectious Diseases-VoA.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man in wearing a suit and seated on a chair in a lab, mixed with shots of female coworkers working with laboratory equipment|Fauci discusses his work in 2020 (4 minutes)]]\nIn 1968, Fauci joined the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH) as a clinical associate in the Laboratory of Clinical Investigation (LCI) at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.<ref name=\"pr1984\"/> In 1974, he became Head of the Clinical Physiology Section, LCI, and in 1980 was appointed Chief of the Laboratory of Immunoregulation. In 1984, he became director of NIAID, a position he still holds as of 2020.<ref name = Grady/> In that role he has the responsibility for an extensive research portfolio of basic and applied research on infectious and immune-mediated illnesses.<ref name=\"pr1984\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Anthony Fauci Named New NIAID Director |url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/assets/media/pdf/press/1984/PR_NIAID_1984_11_02.pdf |website=HHS News |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |format=Press release |date=November 2, 1984 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209135255/https://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/press/1984/PR_NIAID_1984_11_02.pdf |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> He has turned down several offers to lead his agency's parent, the NIH, and has been at the forefront of US efforts to contend with viral diseases like HIV, [[SARS]], the [[2009 swine flu pandemic]], [[MERS]], [[Ebola]] and [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grady |first1=Denise |title=Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html |work=The New York Times |publisher=New York Times Company |date=March 8, 2020 |location=New York |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315113453/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe played a significant role in the early 2000s in creating the [[President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Varmus |first=Harold |title=Making PEPFAR |journal=Science & Diplomacy |date=December 1, 2013 |volume=2 |issue=4 |url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2013/making-pepfar|access-date=December 2, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203002438/http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2013/making-pepfar|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and in driving development of [[biodefense]] drugs and vaccines following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 terrorist attacks]].<ref>Bernard Wysocki Jr for The Wall Street Journal. December 6, 2005 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113383825463714813 Agency Chief Spurs Bioterror Research \u2013 And Controversy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229204855/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113383825463714813 |date=February 29, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a visiting professor at many medical centers, and has received 30 honorary doctorates from universities in the US and abroad.<ref name=\"Cited\"/>\n\n===Medical achievements===\n[[File:President Clinton meets with Dr. Anthony Fauci (14358494424).jpg|thumb|left|President [[Bill Clinton]] visits the NIH in 1995 and hears about the latest advances in HIV/AIDS research from Fauci]]\n[[File:President George W. Bush and Dr. Anthony S. Fauci.jpg|thumb|right|Fauci poses for a photo with [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] in 2007]]\nFauci has made important scientific observations that contributed to the understanding of regulation of the human immune response, and is recognized for delineating the mechanisms whereby [[Immunosuppression|immunosuppressive]] agents adapt to that response. He developed therapies for formerly fatal diseases such as [[polyarteritis nodosa]], [[granulomatosis with polyangiitis]], and [[lymphomatoid granulomatosis]]. In a 1985 [[Stanford University]] Arthritis Center Survey of the American Rheumatism Association, membership ranked Fauci's work on the treatment of polyarteritis nodosa and granulomatosis with polyangiitis as one of the most important advances in patient management in [[rheumatology]] over the previous 20 years.<ref name=\"Holy Cross\">Holy Cross Magazine [http://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/summer02/features/fauci_sidebar.html Anthony S. Fauci, M.D., \u201962] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823163730/http://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/summer02/features/fauci_sidebar.html |date=August 23, 2016 }} Retrieved on May 30, 2007</ref><ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\">{{cite web |title=1998 AACC Lectureship Award |url=https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx |publisher=American Association for Clinical Chemistry |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102191524/https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx |archivedate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:President Obama greets Dr Anthony Fauci 9203044910 l (14352845344).jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] greets Fauci in June 2014]]\nFauci has contributed to the understanding of how [[HIV]] destroys the body's defenses leading to the progression to [[AIDS]]. He has outlined the mechanisms of induction of HIV expression by endogenous [[cytokine]]s.<ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\" /> Fauci has worked to develop strategies for the therapy and immune reconstitution of patients with the disease, as well as for a [[vaccine]] to prevent HIV infection. His current research is concentrated on identifying the nature of the immunopathogenic mechanisms of HIV infection and the scope of the body's immune responses to HIV.\n\nIn 2003, the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] stated that from 1983 to 2002, \"Fauci was the 13th most-cited scientist among the 2.5 to 3 million authors in all disciplines throughout the world who published articles in scientific journals\".<ref name=\"NIAID\"/>\n\n=== Ebola Congressional hearing ===\n{{See also|Ebola virus cases in the United States}}\nOn October 16, 2014, in a United States Congressional hearing regarding the [[Ebola virus]] crisis, Fauci, who, as the director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) had been discussing the importance of screening for weeks,<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2014/10/06/more-ebola-screening-possible-for-united-states Officials eyeing additional screening for Ebola in US, vow to protect citizens from disease] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305023606/http://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2014/10/06/more-ebola-screening-possible-for-united-states |date=March 5, 2016 }}. Associated Press. October 6, 2014.  Retrieved October 16, 2014.</ref> testified that NIAID was still some distance away from producing sufficient quantities of cures or vaccines for widespread trials.<ref name=2014-Guardian-EbolaHearing>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Dan |title=CDC director warns Ebola like 'forest fire' as Congress readies for hearing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/ebola-congress-hearing-cdc-director |work=The Guardian |date=October 16, 2014|access-date=December 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503184455/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/ebola-congress-hearing-cdc-director|archive-date=May 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Specifically, Fauci said, \"While NIAID is an active participant in the global effort to address the public health emergency occurring in west Africa, it is important to recognize that we are still in the early stages of understanding how infection with the Ebola virus can be treated and prevented.\" <ref name=2014-Guardian-EbolaHearing />\n\nFauci also remarked in the hearing: \"As we continue to expedite research while enforcing high safety and efficacy standards, the implementation of the public health measures already known to contain prior Ebola virus outbreaks and the implementation of treatment strategies such as fluid and electrolyte replacement are essential to preventing additional infections, treating those already infected, protecting healthcare providers, and ultimately bringing this epidemic to an end.\"<ref name=2014-Guardian-EbolaHearing />\n\n===COVID-19 task force===\n[[File:White House Coronavirus Update Briefing (49723232743).jpg|thumb|Fauci speaks to the [[White House]] press corps on [[COVID-19]] in March 2020]]\nFauci is a member of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] established in late January 2020, under [[President Trump]], to deal with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=WhatWeKnow>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/27/coronavirus-what-we-know-mike-pence-and-task-force/4891905002/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |title=What we know about the White House coronavirus task force now that Mike Pence is in charge |author=Santucci, Jeanine |date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229101529/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/27/coronavirus-what-we-know-mike-pence-and-task-force/4891905002/ |archive-date= February 29, 2020 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"scimag-22mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title='I'm going to keep pushing.' Anthony Fauci tries to make the White House listen to facts of the pandemic |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/i-m-going-keep-pushing-anthony-fauci-tries-make-white-house-listen-facts-pandemic |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[Science Magazine]] |date=March 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323021843/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/i-m-going-keep-pushing-anthony-fauci-tries-make-white-house-listen-facts-pandemic |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> He said that the final [[case fatality rate]] of those who are infected will likely be closer to 1% than the 2% initially estimated by the [[World Health Organization]], which is ten times the 0.1% reported rate for seasonal flu.<ref>Higgins-Dunn, Noah; Lovelace, Berkely, Jr., [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/top-federal-health-official-says-coronavirus-outbreak-is-going-to-get-worse-in-the-us.html \"Top US health official says the coronavirus is 10 times 'more lethal' than the seasonal flu\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323055620/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/top-federal-health-official-says-coronavirus-outbreak-is-going-to-get-worse-in-the-us.html |date=March 23, 2020 }}, ''[[CNBC]]'', March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>McCormack, John, [https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-the-difference-between-a-1-and-0-1-fatality-rate-is-huge/ \"Coronavirus vs. the Flu: The Difference Between a 1% and 0.1% Fatality Rate Is Huge\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322140426/https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-the-difference-between-a-1-and-0-1-fatality-rate-is-huge/ |date=March 22, 2020 }}, ''[[National Review]]'', March 14, 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trump Has Given Unusual Leeway to Fauci, but Aides Say He's Losing His Patience |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-fauci.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200324&instance_id=17020&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=104839084&section=topNews&segment_id=22704&te=1&user_id=c001b63136aba3268ed514b0835032af |website=The New York Times |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326181422/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-fauci.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200324&instance_id=17020&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=104839084&section=topNews&segment_id=22704&te=1&user_id=c001b63136aba3268ed514b0835032af |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a \"de facto\" public health spokesperson for the office of the President during the pandemic<ref name=2020-Atlantic-Profile>{{cite news |last1=Nicholas |first1=Peter |title=Anthony Fauci\u2019s Plan to Stay Honest |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/anthony-fauci-covid-19-trump-and-staying-healthy/608554/ |work=The Atlantic |date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134643/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/anthony-fauci-covid-19-trump-and-staying-healthy/608554/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-reasons-gov-cuomo-and-dr-fauci-are-americas-de-facto-leaders-during-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2020-03-30 |title=5 reasons Gov. Cuomo and Dr. Fauci are America's de facto leaders during the coronavirus pandemic |last=Smith |first=Virginia K. |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201903/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-reasons-gov-cuomo-and-dr-fauci-are-americas-de-facto-leaders-during-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2020-03-30|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and strong advocate of ongoing social distancing efforts in the United States. On March 29 he argued for the extension of the initial 15-day self-isolation guidelines, issued by the executive office, to at least until the end of April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5812439/trump-coronavirus-measures-fauci/ |title=President Trump's Advisors 'Argued Strongly' Against Easing Coronavirus Measures Too Early, Anthony Fauci Says |website=Time |language=en|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150259/https://time.com/5812439/trump-coronavirus-measures-fauci/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to his disagreements with Trump, Fauci has been criticised by right-wing pundits and received death threats that resulted in the need for a security detail.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/490763-fauci-dismisses-death-threats-its-my-job |title=Fauci dismisses death threats: 'It's my job' |last=Budryk |first=Zack |date=April 2, 2020 |website=TheHill |language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404061334/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/490763-fauci-dismisses-death-threats-its-my-job|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/politics/anthony-fauci-security-detail/index.html |title=Nation's top coronavirus expert Dr. Anthony Fauci forced to beef up security as death threats increase |author1=Kate Bennett |author2=Evan Perez |website=CNN|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402041259/https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/politics/anthony-fauci-security-detail/index.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/01/dr-fauci-security-reportedly-expanded-as-infectious-disease-expert-faces-threats |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403172130/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/01/dr-fauci-security-reportedly-expanded-as-infectious-disease-expert-faces-threats |archive-date=April 3, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> While there have been disagreements, Trump has also praised Fauci.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump offers praise for absent Fauci: 'He's a good man' |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/489145-trump-offers-praise-for-nihs-fauci-hes-a-good-man |work=The Hill |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406151121/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/489145-trump-offers-praise-for-nihs-fauci-hes-a-good-man |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who is Dr Anthony Fauci, the US's trusted voice on coronavirus? |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/dr-anthony-fauci-trusted-voice-coronavirus-200330124431910.html |work=Al Jazeera |date=March 30, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401052651/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/dr-anthony-fauci-trusted-voice-coronavirus-200330124431910.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=How Fauci Prods, Persuades Trump on Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-coronavirus-crisis-deepens-trump-and-fauci-form-complicated-bond-11585682074 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402013651/https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-coronavirus-crisis-deepens-trump-and-fauci-form-complicated-bond-11585682074 |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFauci married [[Christine Grady]], a nurse and [[bioethicist]] with the NIH, in 1985, after they met while treating a patient. Grady is chief of the Department of Bioethics at the [[National Institutes of Health Clinical Center]]. The couple has three adult daughters: Jennifer, Megan, and Alison.<ref name=\"Heavy31320\">{{cite news |last1=Laviola |first1=Erin |title=Christine Grady, Anthony Fauci's Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/christine-grady-anthony-fauci-wife/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Heavy.com |date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140746/https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/christine-grady-anthony-fauci-wife/ |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nFauci is a member of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[National Academy of Medicine]], the [[American Philosophical Society]], and the [[Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters]], as well as other numerous professional societies including the [[American Society for Clinical Investigation]], the [[Infectious Diseases Society of America]], and the [[American Association of Immunologists]]. He serves on the editorial boards of many scientific journals; as an editor of ''[[Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine]]''; and as author, coauthor, or editor of more than 1,000 scientific publications, including several textbooks.<ref name=\"Cited\">Highly Cited [http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 Biography] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120428/http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 |date=September 29, 2007 }} Retrieved May 30, 2007</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:Ben Carson and Anthony Fauci.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ben Carson]] and Anthony Fauci (right) being announced as recipients of the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] at the [[White House]] on June 19, 2008.]]\n* 1979: [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]]<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |title=Press Release Archive: Twelve Outstanding Public Servants Representing the Best and Brightest in Federal Government to be Honored at 53rd Annual Arthur S. Flemming Awards Presented by GW June 11 |url=https://www2.gwu.edu/~media/pressreleases/06-06-02-FlemmingAdvisory.htm |website=www2.gwu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902123738/http://www.gwu.edu/~media/pressreleases/06-06-02-FlemmingAdvisory.htm|archive-date=September 2, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1993: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Bates College]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bates.edu/president/list-of-honorary-degree-recipients/|title=List of Honorary Degree Recipients {{!}} Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, D.Sc. {{!}} Bates College|last=|first=|date=May 31, 1993|website=Bates College|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 10, 2020|quote=Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, D.Sc. (May 31, 1993)}}</ref>\n*1995: [[Ernst Jung Prize]] (shared with Samuel A. Wells, Jr.)<ref>{{cite web |title=All Laureates \u2013 English |url=http://www.jung-stiftung.de/en/die-jung-stiftung-1/ernst-jung-preis-fuer-medizin/alle-preistraeger |publisher=Jung Foundation for Science and Research |accessdate=November 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033100/http://www.jung-stiftung.de/en/die-jung-stiftung-1/ernst-jung-preis-fuer-medizin/alle-preistraeger|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*1995: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Duke University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goduke.com/news/2020/4/2/mens-basketball-dr-fauci-joined-coach-k-for-todays-basketball-beyond.aspx|title=SiriusXM's Basketball and Beyond with Coach K: Dr. Anthony Fauci|website=Duke University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n* 1996: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Colgate University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/july1996/honorary-degrees.html |title=Honoris causa |website=Colgate University | access-date=March 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825105159/http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/july1996/honorary-degrees.html | archive-date=August 25, 2007 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1999: Honorary Doctor of Public Service Degree, [[Shippensburg University of Pennsylvania]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Agencies|first=United States Congress House Committee on Appropriations Subcommittee on the Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Related|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4a7SoQfEz2QC&pg=PA954&lpg=PA954&dq=1999:+Honorary+Doctor+of+Public+Service+Degree,+Shippensburg+University+of+Pennsylvania+fauci&source=bl&ots=MhsDHP48RA&sig=ACfU3U1lsj-_9WWVxxx13X85g3a97pSklg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjquruVyPDoAhVEs54KHY1sDRkQ6AEwAHoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=1999:%20Honorary%20Doctor%20of%20Public%20Service%20Degree,%20Shippensburg%20University%20of%20Pennsylvania%20fauci&f=false|title=Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Related Agencies Appropriations for 2001: Hearings Before a Subcommittee of the Committee on Appropriations, House of Representatives, One Hundred Sixth Congress, Second Session|date=2000|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=978-0-16-060655-7|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2002: [[Albany Medical Center Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Lawrence K. Altman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/28/us/aids-researcher-fauci-wins-prize.html |title=AIDS Researcher Fauci Wins Prize |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 28, 2002 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527213848/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/28/us/aids-researcher-fauci-wins-prize.html |archive-date=May 27, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[American Academy of Achievement]]'s Golden Plate Award<ref name = AAA>{{cite web |title=Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. Biography and Interview |website=achievement.org |publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]] |url=https://www.achievement.org/achiever/anthony-s-fauci-m-d/#interview|access-date=April 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208114942/http://www.achievement.org/achiever/anthony-s-fauci-m-d/#interview|archive-date=February 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[National Medal of Science]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=5300000000430 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details |publisher=[[National Science Foundation]] |date=July 27, 2007 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401062952/https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=5300000000430 |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[American Association of Immunologists Lifetime Achievement Award]]<ref name=\"Winners\">{{cite web |title=Past Recipients |website=The American Association of Immunologists |url=https://www.aai.org/Awards/Career-Awards/AAI-Lifetime-Achievement-Award/Past-Recipients.aspx | access-date=September 19, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919212957/https://www.aai.org/Awards/Career-Awards/AAI-Lifetime-Achievement-Award/Past-Recipients.aspx | archive-date=September 19, 2018 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2007: [[Mary Woodard Lasker Public Service Award]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Altman |first1=Lawrence K. |title=4 Winners of Lasker Medical Prize |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/16/health/16lasker.html?ref=us |work=The New York Times |date=September 16, 2007|access-date=February 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033315/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/16/health/16lasker.html?ref=us|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2007: [[George M. Kober Medal]], [[Association of American Physicians]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gallin |first1=John I. |title=2007 Association of American Physicians George M. Kober Medal: Introduction of Anthony S. Fauci, MD |journal=The Journal of Clinical Investigation |volume=117:3131\u20133135 (2007) |doi=10.1172/JCI33692|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]<ref name = AAA/>\n* 2013: [[Robert Koch Gold Medal]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=81&clang=1 |title=Robert Koch Stiftung - Anthony S. Fauci |website=www.robert-koch-stiftung.de|access-date=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912231646/http://robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=81&clang=1|archive-date=September 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2013: [[Prince Mahidol Award]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.princemahidolaward.org/people/dr-anthony-fauci/ |title=Dr. Anthony Fauci |date=November 21, 2013 |website=Prince Mahidol Award Foundation}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[John Dirks Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]]<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)30050-2/abstract |title=NIAID director wins Canada Gairdner Global Health Award |first=Brian |last=Owens |date=March 26, 2016 |journal=The Lancet |volume=387 |issue=10025 |pages=1261 |via=www.thelancet.com |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)30050-2 |pmid=27017308|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n*2018: Honorary Doctor of Science, Commencement Speaker, [[American University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.american.edu/media/news/20180418-commencement-2018.cfm|title=AU Announces 2018 Commencement Speakers|last=Alex|first=Kelly|last2=April 18|first2=er {{!}}|website=American University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23|last3=2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works and publications==\n{{Scholia|author}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Dale|first2=David C.|last3=Balow|first3=James E.|title=Glucocorticosteroid Therapy: Mechanisms of Action and Clinical Considerations|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=March 1976|volume=84|issue=3|pages=304-15|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-84-3-304|pmid=769625|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/690158/glucocorticosteroid-therapy-mechanisms-action-clinical-considerations?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-84-3-304}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34058573|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Haynes|first2=Barton F.|last3=Katz|first3=Paul|title=The Spectrum of Vasculitis: Clinical, Pathologic, Immunologic, and Therapeutic Considerations|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=November 1, 1978|volume=89|issue=5_Part_1|pages=660|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-89-5-660|pmid=31121|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/692458/spectrum-vasculitis-clinical-pathologic-immunologic-therapeutic-considerations?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-89-5-660}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34049019|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Haynes|first2=Barton F.|last3=Katz|first3=Paul|last4=Wolff|first4=Sheldon M.|title=Wegener's Granulomatosis: Prospective Clinical and Therapeutic Experience With 85 Patients for 21 Years|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=January 1983|volume=98|issue=1|pages=76|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-98-1-76|pmid=6336643|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/696194/wegener-s-granulomatosis-prospective-clinical-therapeutic-experience-85-patients-21?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-98-1-76}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34055385|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|last2=Macher|first2=Abe M.|last3=Longo|first3=Dan L.|last4=Lane|first4=H. Clifford|last5=Rook|first5=Alain H.|last6=Masur|first6=Henry|last7=Gelmann|first7=Edward P.|title=Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome: Epidemiologic, Clinical, Immunologic, and Therapeutic Considerations|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=January 1984|volume=100|issue=1|pages=92|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-100-1-92|pmid=6318629|url=https://annals.org/aim/article-abstract/697649/acquired-immunodeficiency-syndrome-epidemiologic-clinical-immunologic-therapeutic-considerations?doi=10.7326%2f0003-4819-100-1-92}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34055324|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=AS|title=The human immunodeficiency virus: infectivity and mechanisms of pathogenesis|journal=Science|date=February 5, 1988|volume=239|issue=4840|pages=617\u2013622|doi=10.1126/science.3277274|pmid=3277274|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/239/4840/617}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34049376|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Pantaleo|first1=Giuseppe|last2=Graziosi|first2=Cecilia|last3=Fauci|first3=Anthony S.|title=The Immunopathogenesis of Human Immunodeficiency Virus Infection|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|date=February 4, 1993|volume=328|issue=5|pages=327\u2013335|doi=10.1056/NEJM199302043280508|pmid=8093551|url=https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199302043280508}} {{Wikidata+icon|Q34060285|y}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Fauci|first1=Anthony S.|title=Host factors and the pathogenesis of HIV-induced disease|journal=Nature|date=De