n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Unger, Donald N.S., [https://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/2002_03Summer.pdf \"I Saw People Who Were In Pain\"], ''Holy Cross Magazine'', College of the Holy Cross,  v.36, n.3, Summer 2002 issue. Front cover and pp.10-19.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anthony&nbsp;Fauci}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.niaid.nih.gov/about/director Anthony S. Fauci, M.D.] at [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID)\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=Anthony%20S%20Fauci Anthony S. Fauci] at [[PubMed]]\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm2118834|Anthony Fauci}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Biography}}\n\n{{Winners of the National Medal of Science|biological}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fauci, Anthony S.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American immunologists]]\n[[Category:American medical researchers]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:College of the Holy Cross alumni]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:National Institutes of Health people]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Science laureates]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Regis High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Weill Cornell Medical College alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Coronavirus Task Force]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-Italian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Newyorkdetails", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Fauci"}
{"title_page": "Jeffrey Hammer", "text_new": "{{Infobox economist|name=Jeffrey Hammer|birth_date={{birth date and age|1953|11|3}}|image=|birth_name=Jeffrey Stuart Hammer|alma_mater=[[Swarthmore College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]), [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])|institutions=[[Princeton University]], [[The World Bank]]|field=[[Development economics]]<br>[[Health economics]]}}\n\n'''Jeffrey Stuart Hammer''' (born November 3, 1953) is a health and development economist. Hammer was the Charles and Marie Robertson Visiting Professor of Economic Development at the [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]] of [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Das|first=Jishnu|last2=Hammer|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Leonard|first3=Kenneth|date=2008|title=The Quality of Medical Advice in Low Income Countries|url=https://pubs.aeaweb.org/doi/pdf/10.1257/jep.22.2.93|journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives|volume=22|issue=2|pages=93-114|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theigc.org/person/jeffrey-hammer/|title=Jeffrey Hammer - IGC|date=2013-06-01|publisher=International Growth Centre|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>  His primary research focus is the economics of health policy and health service provision in poor countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/future-development/2015/08/28/why-advocating-universal-free-primary-health-care-is-irresponsible-at-best|title=Why advocating universal free primary health care is irresponsible at best|last=Hammer|first=Jeffrey|date=2015-08-28|publisher=The Brookings Institution|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Das|first=Jishnu|last2=Hammer|first2=Jeffrey|date=2007|title=Money for nothing: The dire straits of medical practice in Delhi, India|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304387806000770|journal=Journal of Development Economics|volume=83|issue=1|pages=1-36|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chaudhury|first=Nazmul|last2=Hammer|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Kremer|first3=Michael|last4=Muralidharan|first4=Karthik|date=2006|title=Missing in Action: Teacher and Health Worker Absence in Developing Countries.|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/089533006776526058|journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives|volume=20|issue=1|pages=91-116|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hammer|first=Jeffrey|last2=Spears|first2=Dean|date=2016|title=Village sanitation and child health: Effects and external validity in a randomized field experiment in rural India|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167629616300030|journal=Journal of Health Economics|volume=48|pages=135-148|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He was on the core team of the 2004 [[World Development Report]] \u201cMaking Services Work for Poor People,\u201d alongside [[Lant Pritchett]], [[Shanta Devarajan]], and other notable economists.<ref>{{cite book|first=World Bank|title=World Development Report 2004|publisher=[[The World Bank]]|year=2003|doi=10.1596/0-8213-5468-X}}</ref>\u00a0 He is currently a senior non-resident scholar at the [[National Council of Applied Economic Research]] in Delhi, and Director of the [https://onehundredhomes.in/ One Hundred Homes] project.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncaer.org/expert_details.php?pID=204|title=Jeffrey S. Hammer|publisher=National Council of Applied Economic Research|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://onehundredhomes.in/about|title=One Hundred Homes|publisher=One Hundred Homes|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Education and career ==\nHammer earned a B.A. in Economics from [[Swarthmore College]] and his PhD in Economics from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] where he was the recipient of a [[NSF-GRFP|National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship]].<ref name=\":0\" />\u00a0 Before Princeton he worked at [[World Bank|The World Bank]] for 25 years, the last three years in the New Delhi office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.worldbank.org/team/jeffrey-hammer|title=Jeffrey Hammer|author=<!--Not stated-->|publisher=The World Bank|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hammer, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World Bank people]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Development economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Health economists]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox economist|name=Jeffrey Hammer|birth_date={{birth date and age|1953|11|3}}|image=|birth_name=Jeffrey Stuart Hammer|alma_mater=[[Swarthmore College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]), [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])|institutions=[[Princeton University]], [[The World Bank]]|field=[[Development economics]]<br>[[Health economics]]}}\n\n'''Jeffrey Stuart Hammer''' (born November 3, 1953) is a health and development economist. Hammer was the Charles and Marie Robertson Visiting Professor of Economic Development at the [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]] of [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Das|first=Jishnu|last2=Hammer|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Leonard|first3=Kenneth|date=2008|title=The Quality of Medical Advice in Low Income Countries|url=https://pubs.aeaweb.org/doi/pdf/10.1257/jep.22.2.93|journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives|volume=22|issue=2|pages=93-114|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theigc.org/person/jeffrey-hammer/|title=Jeffrey Hammer - IGC|date=2013-06-01|publisher=International Growth Centre|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>  His primary research focus is the economics of health policy and health service provision in poor countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/future-development/2015/08/28/why-advocating-universal-free-primary-health-care-is-irresponsible-at-best|title=Why advocating universal free primary health care is irresponsible at best|last=Hammer|first=Jeffrey|date=2015-08-28|publisher=The Brookings Institution|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Das|first=Jishnu|last2=Hammer|first2=Jeffrey|date=2007|title=Money for nothing: The dire straits of medical practice in Delhi, India|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304387806000770|journal=Journal of Development Economics|volume=83|issue=1|pages=1-36|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chaudhury|first=Nazmul|last2=Hammer|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Kremer|first3=Michael|last4=Muralidharan|first4=Karthik|date=2006|title=Missing in Action: Teacher and Health Worker Absence in Developing Countries.|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/089533006776526058|journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives|volume=20|issue=1|pages=91-116|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Hammer|first=Jeffrey|last2=Spears|first2=Dean|date=2016|title=Village sanitation and child health: Effects and external validity in a randomized field experiment in rural India|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167629616300030|journal=Journal of Health Economics|volume=48|pages=135-148|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He was on the core team of the 2004 [[World Development Report]] \u201cMaking Services Work for Poor People,\u201d alongside [[Lant Pritchett]], [[Shanta Devarajan]], and other notable economists.<ref>{{cite book|first=World Bank|title=World Development Report 2004|publisher=[[The World Bank]]|year=2003|doi=10.1596/0-8213-5468-X|authorlink=World Bank|contributor-first=Shantayanan|contributor-last=Devarajan|contributor2-first=Ritva|contributor2-last=Reinikka|contributor3-first=Jeffrey|contributor3-last=Hammer}}</ref>\u00a0 He is currently a senior non-resident scholar at the [[National Council of Applied Economic Research]] in Delhi, and Director of the [https://onehundredhomes.in/ One Hundred Homes] project.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncaer.org/expert_details.php?pID=204|title=Jeffrey S. Hammer|publisher=National Council of Applied Economic Research|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://onehundredhomes.in/about|title=One Hundred Homes|publisher=One Hundred Homes|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Education and career ==\nHammer earned a B.A. in Economics from [[Swarthmore College]] and his PhD in Economics from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] where he was the recipient of a [[NSF-GRFP|National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship]].<ref name=\":0\" />\u00a0 Before Princeton he worked at [[World Bank|The World Bank]] for 25 years, the last three years in the New Delhi office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.worldbank.org/team/jeffrey-hammer|title=Jeffrey Hammer|author=<!--Not stated-->|publisher=The World Bank|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hammer, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World Bank people]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Development economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Health economists]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Econohammer", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Hammer"}
